Ah, a delightful problem involving modular arithmetic!  To find the remainder when a polynomial is divided by a linear expression, we can leverage the powerful tool of the Remainder Theorem.  

Let's denote our polynomial as  $P(x) = (5x + 9)^{611} + (x + 5)^{11} + (x - 1)^{11} + 3x^2 + 1$.  We want to find the value of $P(-2)$, as this will be the remainder upon division by $x+2$.

Substituting $x=-2$ into our polynomial, we get:

\begin{align*}
P(-2) &= (5(-2) + 9)^{611} + (-2 + 5)^{11} + (-2 - 1)^{11} + 3(-2)^2 + 1 \\
&= (-1)^{611} + 3^{11} + (-3)^{11} + 12 + 1 \\
&= -1 + 177147 - 177147 + 13 \\
&= \boxed{13}
\end{align*} 



Therefore, the remainder when $P(x)$ is divided by $x+2$ is $\boxed{13}$.

